I have been dealing with chronic pain, pain managment, pharmacies, insurance companies and doctors offices staffs for about 5 years now, and Dr. Nasser and his staff "is second to none" truly the best in all they do, they have been my care provider since Aug 2016. Behind every great physician is a greater staff, Myah the call nurse is the saint that handles issues that patients may have outside regular scheduled appointments. If you have an issue and call in this is where your call is transferred to.  While being on suboxone I have had several occasions where I had issues with refills I.e needed prior approvals, needed early refill due to fear of running out while on travel, ive had issues with my insurance, and several times I procrastinated  making my follow up Appointments that would put me in jeopardy of running out of my medication before I could be seen. And every time I called on her for help she has always responded back within the hour or at the next business day at the latest with good news... If you have an opioid dependency or have ever been on an opioid medication then you can understand the anxiety that you experience when running out of meds when you are on vacation or when on travel for work. But unlike my past experiences with other health care providers of being treated like a junkie and getting the run around or Just getting the infamous sacastic " sorrry but there is nothing I can do".. My experience with Dr Masih was pleasurable, however, far less could be said about the attentive nature of the staff.  First, the selection process of an "in Network" provider was not the first option provided in scheduling a medical procedure thus the consideration of the out of pocket cost to the client was not considered.  Secondly, Upon arriving at the hospital for the second procedure, the paperwork noting the procedure to be performed was not correct; the first procedure was nearly repeated if it weren't for my questioning.  Lastly, the follow up with billing inquiries is/was not processed timely.  I made several calls over a 1 week period (Sadie & Lorraine) to be told the inquiry has not been reviewed and additional time will be needed.  After 4 calls and 9 transfers Office Manager Lydia Baker advised " I am too busy to review your information and I will need to call you back" and without my acknowledgment,  the call was disconnected.  I am hugely disappointed with the level of service received as well as the competence of the staff; I found Lydia to be extremely rude and unapologetic for the delay in the response time experienced.   I would recommend increased customer service training for ALL staff members as well as a review of office procedures regarding timely follow up.< /review>

<Rating>3<//Rating><review>I went here two days ago while visiting a friend in the Long Beach area. Yen has several other locations, including the one near my home in Studio City.

The first thing I noticed when I got here was that this was a Korean owned franchise. Oh no. The menu consisted mainly of contemporary fancy rolls, as well as some other basic "Japanese" food that anybody can learn to cook really. Anyways, I gave the food a shot.

I ordered yellowtail, albacore, and spanish mackerel nigiri sushi. Then my friend got a soft shell crab and salmon roll. After having tried a piece of everything, I concluded that the food here is 3 stars. It's not bad sushi like Todai or Sushi Mac. It's even a tad better than Mon, which is another Korean owned sushi franchise. It's just not on the same freshness/taste level as Noshi Sushi, Sushi Gen, Yotsuya, or even Oomasa. The rolls themselves were just okay too.

Sure, the restaurant interior is nice, clean, and good for friendship outings. But if you want something great tasting, don't drive out of your way to eat here. It's not all that spectacular. I guess now I now how the Studio City location probably tastes like.</review>< Pictures>
None</Pictures>

<review>I was a sceptic, to say the least! I filled out one of those online questioners to "just see" what interest rate I could get. I was at a 4%, which isn't terrible but lets be real, I was seeing rates under 3% and even under 2%!! I thought, I can use that extra money!! So, I kid you not, I got probably 100 calls from various Lending companies. It became a super annoyance! However, I tried to be polite and listen. Zack Neelands from Generation Lending happen to be of these calls. For some reason he seemed like less pressure, or kinder or maybe authentic. Not really trying to sell as much as educate. However, the vet seemed to think it was an intestinal issue and claimed that he saw nothing wrong, he barely examinedher mouth in front of us, he was so sure of himself that he didn't listen to us, the owners. So we were skeptical when we left, and had near insisted that it was her teeth and we felt they should have xrayed her mouth but they did not. After a week of antibiotics, nothing changed so we called and complained and they "squeezed us in" an additional week later, it should have been sooner and they should have made more of an effort to do so when I complained that the vet had overlooked the issue. There is no way that in one week her tooth and the gums around it would become so bad (they called it necrotic.) They had failed to listen to us when we insisted that it was a tooth problem (seeing as we had past experiences with the issue.)
Our poor dog had to suffer an extra two weeks due to them! She was REALLY bad and we couldn't afford to take her to the E.R. having just paid for her previous appointment and the body (excluding the head) xrays and medication they gave her. We are long time customers, but we are disgusted and dismayed by our experience and their lack of professionalism.
We are now shopping for a new vet.

Now, I didn't have service at the time of the call so I didn't know about this until a few hours later when I regained cell service. When I did regain cell service I found out the real series of events that took place. An employee at San Joaquin took my dog to the play area, while in the play area my dog somehow got out and instead of the employee going in to get help to get my dog back, they didn't mention anything. So no one, besides the employee responsible for my dog, knew she was missing. When the caller found my dog, she immediately took her to San Joaquin to see if she was chipped (because she had no collar on), which is how she got my information, the caller then took my dog back to her place of work (down the street from San Joaquin) for over 2 hours!
